notes: Sift|Pheidole, Attini, Paratrechina, Octostruma|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33|||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Winkler||Met Harry, Dunia and Manuel in Quebrada Grande at 7. Walked up from leaving the 4-Runner at 8:21. Gtraps open and bait out at 9:30. Windy and rainy in the morning, and windy and clear in the afternoon. Temperature around 14C. Photos of sun and cloug. GigaPan taken at the same spot as in December 201. Should be a collembola visible (photo 5287). Spider monkeys around but no notice of me was taken. Walked Sendero del Caro until first small peak after the trail splits (I`d gone to the right). Wet at the start, but VERY dry where I sampled. notes: Bait|Atta, black phediole, Crematogaster. Video of Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis @ 200x|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33||http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-RLJZr1XR2I|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Sift|Small myrmicinae, common Gnaptogenys, medium sized myrmicinae|Traps out and bait down at 9am. Gigapan taken uphill from the creek under a fantastic canopy tree. Should be a Pachycondyla visible on the rock of the upstream direction. Temperature was 18-21C all day. Toledo birds singing after 12. 1 Agoti. Large ambulatory ponerinae and Gnaptogenys dominate here. notes: Winkler|Likely nothing|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. notes: Pitfall||Walked up from the truck in 25 minuts to the Malaise trap at Sendero Circular. Traps out and bait down at 9:15am. At 9:20 something very large, and black/gray moved past the far side of the Malaise trap. I thought tapir, and Manuel later agreed. Unfortunately, no photo. GigaPan was 22x48 at Bait Station 1 and the Malaise trap. Appeared over exposed and flat colours. 16-20C today. Leaf litter is dry. Many large, ambulatory ponerines around (video). Also video of the small myrmicinae at bait 6. This bait station was raided for two tubes (photo) and the tuna can and all the tuna. Perhaps a Collared Peccary. Traps up at 3:00pm. 5hr sampling.|Waypoint 37|||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71739/|http://bit.ly/g7JDay|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Winkler||Met Harry, Dunia and Manuel in Quebrada Grande at 7. Walked up from leaving the 4-Runner at 8:21. Gtraps open and bait out at 9:30. Windy and rainy in the morning, and windy and clear in the afternoon. Temperature around 14C. Photos of sun and cloug. GigaPan taken at the same spot as in December 201. Should be a collembola visible (photo 5287). Spider monkeys around but no notice of me was taken. Video of small myrmicins under gigapan, slow moving adelomyrmex at bait 1, and black pheidole with abundant soldiers at bait 5.|Waypoint 34|IMG_6578.JPG||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71665/|http://bit.ly/eY3FM9|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Bait|Many small black Solenopsoids, (video), Pheidole, Pachycondyla|Traps out and bait down at 9am. Gigapan taken uphill from the creek under a fantastic canopy tree. Should be a Pachycondyla visible on the rock of the upstream direction. Temperature was 18-21C all day. Toledo birds singing after 12. 1 Agoti. Large ambulatory ponerinae and Gnaptogenys dominate here. Video of Pachycondyla, fight with bodies cut in half and lost legs, many small black Solenopsis-oids, small Pheidole colony entrance and Gnaptogenys burrowing into obscured colony entrance. 5hrs sampling. |Waypoint 38|IMG_6606.JPG|http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q0exb7rUUTw|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71757/|http://bit.ly/hLjiSP |https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|

notes: Winkler|Wasmania |8mEPE|Waypoint 181||Dominant taxa here is the small yellow Myrmicinae (Wasmania) with the black spot on the gaster. Everywhere in the hundreds and thousands. This with the unfortunate (?) Solenopsis invicta from Gongora is also here. Video of Pachycondyla apicalis, Wasmania and other insects taken. 360 GigaPan taken in the middle of the stream near station 6. Howler monkeys, blue morphos cicadeas calling and `leopard` frogs. Almost no rain. On Page 127 of book. |http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/66821/|http://bit.ly/ewci2R|http://sites.google.com/site/acgdecembercollections/|

notes: Bait||5mEPE|Waypoint 194||Arrived and registered. Walked Sendero del Caro until first small peak after the trail splits (I`d gone to the right). Wet at the start, but VERY dry where I sampled. Windy, sunny and the temperature rose from 24 - 27C while I was sampling. All traps down at 8:22am. 41 km from here to Rincon, 25 to Cacao, and 21 to Orosi. 360 Gigapan taken between 2 & 3. Videos taken of the dominant Pheidoles (black and yellow). Crematogaster, Pseudomyrmex and the Labidus|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/66906/|http://bit.ly/fFqImT |http://sites.google.com/site/acgdecembercollections/|Worker
sequencing_centers: Biodiversity Institute of Ontario|Biodiversity Institute of Ontario

institution_storing: Research Collection of M. Alex Smith
notes: Bait|Tiny yellow myrmicines|Met Harry, Dunia and Manuel in Quebrada Grande at 7. Walked up from leaving the 4-Runner at 8:21. Gtraps open and bait out at 9:30. Windy and rainy in the morning, and windy and clear in the afternoon. Temperature around 14C. Photos of sun and cloug. GigaPan taken at the same spot as in December 201. Should be a collembola visible (photo 5287). Spider monkeys around but no notice of me was taken. Video of small myrmicins under gigapan, slow moving adelomyrmex at bait 1, and black pheidole with abundant soldiers at bait 5.|Waypoint 34|IMG_6578.JPG||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71665/|http://bit.ly/eY3FM9|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker
sequencing_centers: Biodiversity Institute of Ontario|Biodiversity Institute of Ontario

institution_storing: Research Collection of M. Alex Smith
notes: Bait|Camponotus, Pheidole*2, Solenopsis (tonnes of)|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33|||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker
sequencing_centers: Biodiversity Institute of Ontario|Biodiversity Institute of Ontario

institution_storing: Research Collection of M. Alex Smith
notes: Sift|small myrmicinae, Gnaptogenys|Walked up from the truck in 25 minuts to the Malaise trap at Sendero Circular. Traps out and bait down at 9:15am. At 9:20 something very large, and black/gray moved past the far side of the Malaise trap. I thought tapir, and Manuel later agreed. Unfortunately, no photo. GigaPan was 22x48 at Bait Station 1 and the Malaise trap. Appeared over exposed and flat colours. 16-20C today. Leaf litter is dry. Many large, ambulatory ponerines around (video). Also video of the small myrmicinae at bait 6. This bait station was raided for two tubes (photo) and the tuna can and all the tuna. Perhaps a Collared Peccary. Traps up at 3:00pm. 5hr sampling.|Waypoint 37|||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71739/|http://bit.ly/g7JDay|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker
sequencing_centers: Biodiversity Institute of Ontario|Biodiversity Institute of Ontario

institution_storing: Research Collection of M. Alex Smith
notes: Winkler|14 hrs|We left the truck at 8:15 and it took almost exactly 1 hr to hike up to the Cima - 500m up. Traps out and bait down at 9:45. Very still, many flies and hummingbirds. Most commonly encountered ants were Gnaptogenys and thin Pachycondyla. Videos of Gnaptogenys, tiny Myrmicinae and small Dolichoderinae. Traps up at 2:30.|Waypoint 39|IMG_6611.JPG||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/72097/|http://bit.ly/fuwb5Q|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Sift|small myrmicinae, Gnaptogenys|Walked up from the truck in 25 minuts to the Malaise trap at Sendero Circular. Traps out and bait down at 9:15am. At 9:20 something very large, and black/gray moved past the far side of the Malaise trap. I thought tapir, and Manuel later agreed. Unfortunately, no photo. GigaPan was 22x48 at Bait Station 1 and the Malaise trap. Appeared over exposed and flat colours. 16-20C today. Leaf litter is dry. Many large, ambulatory ponerines around (video). Also video of the small myrmicinae at bait 6. This bait station was raided for two tubes (photo) and the tuna can and all the tuna. Perhaps a Collared Peccary. Traps up at 3:00pm. 5hr sampling.|Waypoint 37|||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71739/|http://bit.ly/g7JDay|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Winkler||Met Harry, Dunia and Manuel in Quebrada Grande at 7. Walked up from leaving the 4-Runner at 8:21. Gtraps open and bait out at 9:30. Should be a collembola visible (photo 5287). Spider monkeys around but no notice of me was taken. notes: Winkler|2 small Myrmicinae|10mEPE|Waypoint 192||Isidro (Caca0o 2009) let me in the locked gate - didn`t recognise me at first. Walked up from 7:45-9:00 to 1200m. Traps open and bait down at 9:33. Very windy rain, and cloud too - 14C. Can feel ground moving as roots are shifted by the wind. Tarp up. Very dominant/common ant was Gnaptogenys - all traps, baits, sifts, searches. Video of Gnapto at Bait 4. 360 GigaPan (17x48) taken at ~Sift 1. Moist. Malaise trap erected at Santa Rosa at 6:30am. Page 132 in book.|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/66885/|http://bit.ly/gJZD7p |http://sites.google.com/site/acgdecembercollections/|

notes: Bait|Camponotus, Pheidole*2, Solenopsis (tonnes of)|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33|||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Bait|Solenopsis, Pheidole, Paratrechina|11m EPE|Waypoint 178||Drove to the near side of the bridge just before Gongora and left car there and walked up. Can hear construction below. Traps and bait out at 8:30am. Many stout, red-haired gastered ponerines. Video of them cutting something. P. apicalis seem afraid of them. Video of atta, Video of Strumigenys, Video of Extatoma on branch. 360 GigaPan taken at 3/4 on the trail. Page 125 of book. Stout ponerines and Solenopsis are dominant here. |http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/66774/|http://bit.ly/hlkYnt |http://sites.google.com/site/acgdecembercollections/|Worker

notes: Bait|Many small black Solenopsoids, (video), Pheidole, Pachycondyla|Traps out and bait down at 9am. Gigapan taken uphill from the creek under a fantastic canopy tree. Should be a Pachycondyla visible on the rock of the upstream direction. Temperature was 18-21C all day. Toledo birds singing after 12. 1 Agoti. Large ambulatory ponerinae and Gnaptogenys dominate here. notes: Bait||5mEPE|Waypoint 194||Arrived and registered. Walked Sendero del Caro until first small peak after the trail splits (I`d gone to the right). Wet at the start, but VERY dry where I sampled. Windy, sunny and the temperature rose from 24 - 27C while I was sampling. All traps down at 8:22am. 41 km from here to Rincon, 25 to Cacao, and 21 to Orosi. 360 Gigapan taken between 2 & 3. Videos taken of the dominant Pheidoles (black and yellow). Crematogaster, Pseudomyrmex and the Labidus|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/66906/|http://bit.ly/fFqImT |http://sites.google.com/site/acgdecembercollections/|Worker

notes: Winkler||Met Harry, Dunia and Manuel in Quebrada Grande at 7. Walked up from leaving the 4-Runner at 8:21. Gtraps open and bait out at 9:30. Windy and rainy in the morning, and windy and clear in the afternoon. Temperature around 14C. Photos of sun and cloug. GigaPan taken at the same spot as in December 201. Should be a collembola visible (photo 5287). Spider monkeys around but no notice of me was taken. Video of small myrmicins under gigapan, slow moving adelomyrmex at bait 1, and black pheidole with abundant soldiers at bait 5.|Waypoint 34|IMG_6578.JPG||http://gigapan.org/gigapans/71665/|http://bit.ly/eY3FM9|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Sift|Pheidole, Attini, Paratrechina, Octostruma|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33|||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Winkler|14 hrs|We left the truck at 8:15 and it took almost exactly 1 hr to hike up to the Cima - 500m up. Traps out and bait down at 9:45. Very still, many flies and hummingbirds. Most commonly encountered ants were Gnaptogenys and thin Pachycondyla. Videos of Gnaptogenys, tiny Myrmicinae and small Dolichoderinae. Traps up at 2:30.|Waypoint 39|IMG_6611.JPG||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/72097/|http://bit.ly/fuwb5Q|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Pitfall|Rainy day - but nearly all have ants|26mEPE|Waypoint 179||Late-ish start with Harry R. who needs to return by 2pm. Traps etc. out and open at 9:00am. Raining all morning with very strong gusting wind. Sifted fallen logs (Hypoponera-oids) and fallen canopy log for some `new` Doliochoderina. Video taken of the dominan Aphaenogaster taken at bait 4. notes: Bait|Many small black Solenopsoids, (video), Pheidole, Pachycondyla|Traps out and bait down at 9am. Gigapan taken uphill from the creek under a fantastic canopy tree. Should be a Pachycondyla visible on the rock of the upstream direction. Temperature was 18-21C all day. Toledo birds singing after 12. 1 Agoti. Large ambulatory ponerinae and Gnaptogenys dominate here. Video of Pachycondyla, fight with bodies cut in half and lost legs, many small black Solenopsis-oids, small Pheidole colony entrance and Gnaptogenys burrowing into obscured colony entrance. 5hrs sampling. |Waypoint 38|IMG_6606.JPG|http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q0exb7rUUTw|http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71757/|http://bit.ly/hLjiSP |https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|

notes: Bait|Atta, black phediole, Crematogaster. Video of Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis @ 200x|Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. notes: We used a single haploid  male (e.g., Fig. 1A) to facilitate de novo assembly. This focal  male had the Gp-9 B genotype (1) and was the offspring of a Gp-  9 Bb queen from a multiple-queen colony originally collected near  Athens, Georgia, in 2008. Upon transfer of the colony to the  laboratory, the queen was isolated with workers for 1 year to  ensure that all progeny in the colony were her offspring.  A Roche 454 shotgun sequencing library and an Illumina  paired-end library (insert size estimated from gel: 330 bp) were  built from the DNA of the single focal haploid male. "Complete mitochondrial genomes were generated for  four individuals from three closely related Solenopsis  species. The two S. invicta samples were collected in  Pascagoula, MS (PMS) and Vera, MS (VMS), S. geminata  was collected in Tallahassee, FL, and S. richteri  was collected in Rosario, Argentina. Even though the  two S. invicta mitogenomes were sequenced from specimens  collected in the invasive range, the ~1 kb coxI/  tRNA-L2/coxII section of these mitogenomes are identical to haplotypes from the native range (PMS is  H22 [GenBank: AY249114]; VMS is H5 [GenBank:  AY249097]) and represent two widely divergent clades  within S. invicta and two geographically and genetically  distinct populations (Argentina and Brazil)" Wurm et al. The genome of the fire ant Solenopsis invicta. PNAS. 2011. 108(14): 5679-5684. Gotzek et al. Mitochondrial genome evolution in fire ants  (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). BMC Evolutionary Biology 2010, 10:300

notes: Pitfall||Set up Connor for the day working on Cacao 1999 malaise traps (2 in the day). Switching rental vehicles at 3pm. Completely clear, somewhat breezy and ciccadas calling all day. Very hot (>30 C). Traps out and bait down at 9:20am. GigaPan at Bait 6 was problematic (batteries died and the shutter arm fell off). took about 4hrs to finish with a hard re-start. Ticks everywhere. Videos of Atta at Bait 2, Large Camponotus at Bait 5, Crematogaster, Atta and Solenopsis at Bait 3 and Small Camponotus at Bait 4. All up at 2:50pm. Dominant species, Paratrechina and Solenopsis|Waypoint 33|||http://www.gigapan.org/gigapans/71622/|http://bit.ly/dQDt90|https://sites.google.com/site/acgantcollectionsfeb2011/|Worker

notes: Winkler|Poneromorph and myrmicinae|10mEPE|Waypoint 192||Isidro (Caca0o 2009) let me in the locked gate - didn`t recognise me at first. Walked up from 7:45-9:00 to 1200m. Very dominant/common ant was Gnaptogenys - all traps, baits, sifts, searches. Video of Gnapto at Bait 4. 360 GigaPan (17x48) taken at ~Sift 1. Moist. Malaise trap erected at Santa Rosa at 6:30am.
